# Changelog discipline

- Before **any changelog edit** tied to new product/docs/test work, confirm workflow order: run the **quality gate** in one terminal — [testing-terminal-isolation.mdc](testing-terminal-isolation.mdc) — `yarn testbatch:verify` when product or test sources changed (see [eslint-typescript.mdc](eslint-typescript.mdc)); then Storybook updates/checks for affected **`src/components/**`** UI (**`yarn storybook:run`** / **`yarn storybook:build`** as needed; layout/page Storybook previews do not require Docs/autodocs); then changelog update. When you **only** adjust **`i18n/*/documents/changeLog.md`** files in a **follow-up** commit after verified work, you may **skip** re-running **`yarn testbatch:verify`** per the **changelog-only** rule in [testing-terminal-isolation.mdc](testing-terminal-isolation.mdc); if **uncertain**, run the gate anyway.
- After **substantive** product or user-visible changes, update [changeLog.md](i18n/en-US/documents/changeLog.md) using the existing [package.json](package.json) `version` as the only version source per [fantasia-changelog-en-us skill](../skills/fantasia-changelog-en-us/SKILL.md).
- Immediately before editing changelog content, re-read [package.json](package.json) and use that live `version` value; do not rely on previously cached values.
- When preparing changelog updates, also inspect `.cursor/plans/` for plan files that match the current `package.json.version` to gather release-context notes for what changed.
- **NEVER, EVER, UNDER ANY CIRCUMSTANCES** auto-bump, infer, or mutate any version value in `package.json` or changelog headings.
- **Always** append or edit changelog content under the section that matches the current `package.json.version`, unless the user explicitly asks for a manual version change.
- **Do not** turn the in-app changelog into an internal QA or CI log: **omit** bullets whose only substance is that maintainers re-ran `yarn testbatch:verify`, `yarn testbatch:ensure:nochange`, `yarn testbatch:ensure:change`, `yarn lint:eslint`, `yarn lint:typescript`, `yarn lint:stylelint`, `yarn test:unit`, production `yarn quasar:build:electron`, Playwright component runs, E2E runs, Storybook smoke/visual runs, or other verification (“all tests passed”, “pipeline green”). Those belong in commits, PRs, or team notes. The changelog is for **what changed** for users or the shipped product, not **how** it was validated.
- **Omit** any `###` category (`New features`, `Known issues`, `Bugfixes & Optimizations`, etc.) when there is nothing to list — no empty sections and no “none” placeholder bullets.
- **`changeLog.md` is a vue-i18n message**: avoid literal **`{`…`}`** in Markdown — they are parsed as interpolation placeholders and can throw **message compilation** errors in-app (including **`Invalid token in placeholder`** when the inner text looks like code, e.g. **`{ force: true }`**). This applies to shell glob brace expansion (**`*.{vue,css}`**), **JS/TS object literals**, and **quoted API snippets** that still contain raw braces. Describe globs without brace expansion; rephrase code examples without **`{...}`**; see [fantasia-changelog-en-us skill](../skills/fantasia-changelog-en-us/SKILL.md).

## TypeScript interfaces and types (`types/`)

- Put shared `interface` / `type` declarations in repository-root `types/` (import with `app/types/...`). Prefer one domain-oriented module per feature area with brief JSDoc on exports (see `types/I_appMenusDataList.ts`). Do not add colocated `<filename>.types.ts` under `src/`, `src-electron/`, or `.storybook-workspace/`. Ambient augmentations for third-party modules also live under `types/` and are loaded with a side-effect import from the owning boot file or `src/stores/index.ts` (see `types/piniaModuleAugmentation.ts`).
- For JavaScript (`.js`), TypeScript (`.ts`), Vue (`.vue`), and JSON (`.json`, `.jsonc`, `.json5`) files, enforce expanded multi-line object literals via ESLint (`object-curly-newline` + `object-property-newline`) and keep files auto-fixable with `eslint --fix`.
